Permit Term #5: Heavy rains during the first week of December 2014 (per the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers gage at Warm Springs Dam) caused a significant volume of water to accumulate in the reservoir prior to December 15, even though the 6 inch bypass gate was open.  Before the water could be evacuated from the reservoir additional rainfall started on December 8, 2014 and continued for the next several days, reaching a peak daily intensity of 5.88 inches on December 11 (see attached ACOE Warm Springs Dam daily operations report).  Per the NOAA Atlas 14 Point Precipitation Frequency web site this 24-hour total was a 5-year event (see attached NOAA Point Precipitation Frequency Estimate).  The return frequency for smaller durations was likely higher.  The reservoir spilled on December 11, and the flow at USGS gaging station #11467000 (Russian River Near Guerneville) exceeded flood stage on December 11 and/or 12 (see attached hydrograph).  Measurable rainfall resumed on December 14 and continued for the next 8 consecutive days ending on December 22, 2014.  Clearly there was an overabundance of natural flow in the first half of December 2014, and under the ensuing climatic conditions it was impractical to evacuate the reservoir of water collected prior to December 15.
